Name: Voyager
Description: Elements relevant to the Voyager 1 and/or Voyager 2 spacecraft mission.

Name: legacy_label_VICAR1
Description: The now-obsolete "VICAR-1" label that was originally attached to the image. To the extent possible, the information is captured in normal VICAR-2 and PDS4 labels. The labels are being retained for historical documentation purposes, and in case there is any question about how the rest of the label items were derived. Contemporaneous Voyager documentation sometimes refers to these legacy labels.

Name: ISS
Description: Attributes relevant to the Voyager Imaging Science Subsystem (ISS) instrument and its observations.

Name: Image_State
Description: Information about an image taken by the Voyager Imaging Science Subsystem (ISS) instrument.

Name: gain_mode_id
Description: The gain state of an instrument. Gain is a constant value, set by the observer, that indicates the approximate number of photon-excited electrons registered by the detector that correlate to one "data number" (DN). Source Data Product Origin: Keyword GAIN_MODE_ID

Name: High
Description: The higher of the two gain states for Voyager ISS

Name: Low
Description: The lower of the two gain states for Voyager ISS

Name: scan_mode_id
Description: Scan rate of vidicon readout. The instrument scan rate affects the radiometric properties of the camera because of the dark current buildup on the vidicon. Values can be '1:1', '2:1', '3:1', '5:1', and '10:1'. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword SCAN_MODE_ID
Vidicon readout was at one-tenth speed.
Vidicon readout was at full speed.
Vidicon readout was at one-half speed.
Vidicon readout was at one-third speed.
Vidicon readout was at one-fifth speed.

Name: edit_mode_id
Description: Edit mode of the camera, indicates amount of data read from the vidicon. '1:1' indicates the full-resolution of the vidicon. Other values include '3:4', '1:2', '1:3', '1:5', and '1:10'. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword EDIT_MODE_ID

Name: Image_Description
Description: Attributes describing an image taken by the Voyager Imaging Science Subsystem (ISS) instrument.

Name: source_product_target_name
Description: The value of TARGET_NAME as given in the source product label. The relationship between this value and the actual intentions of the observer is unknown. The most accurate, though potentially flawed identification of the intended target is given in the Target_Identification class elsewhere in the label. This attribute is included in the PDS4 label for historical reasons. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword TARGET_NAME

Name: image_id
Description: Image identification, takes the form: nnnnes+ddd, where 'nnnn' = picture sequence number for a given day, 'e' = planet of encounter (J=Jupiter, S=Saturn, U=Uranus, N=Neptune), 's' = Voyager spacecraft (1 or 2), - sign indicates before and a + sign indicates after closest planetary approach. 'ddd' = number of days from closest approach. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword IMAGE_ID

Name: image_number
Description: Flight Data Subsystem (FDS) clock count at time of image acquisition. There is a unique IMAGE_NUMBER for each image in a planetary encounter. The clock count is always a seven digit value, five digits to the left of the decimal point and two digits to the right of the decimal point. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword IMAGE_NUMBER

Name: image_time
Description: Time at which the image was acquired. The image_time element is duplicated from the source product label. It provides the time of shutter close calculated from spacecraft clock using both the coarse (seconds) and fine (subRTI) counters (UTC). (A subRTI is approximately 4 msec (1/256 second)). The value is identical to that given in start_time_doy, and start_date_time. Although it is redundant, it is retained here for historical reasons. When the shutter was inhibited (ie SHUTTER_STATE_ID=”DISABLED”), the IMAGE_TIME = START_TIME = STOP_TIME, and all three represent the start of the exposure window during the prepare cycle of the image. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword IMAGE_TIME

Name: earth_received_time
Description: Time at which the image was received at Earth. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword EARTH_RECEIVED_TIME

Name: filter_name
Description: Optical filter used for the image. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword FILTER_NAME

Name: Blue
Description: NAC Filter #2 or WAC Filter #1, spanning portions of the Visible spectrum from 0.43 to 0.53 microns

Name: CH4/JS
Description: WAC Filter #0, spanning portions of the Visible spectrum from 0.614 to 0.624 microns. Also called CH4_JS or METHANE-JST.

Name: CH4/U
Description: WAC Filter #6, spanning portions of the Visible spectrum from 0.536 to 0.546 microns. Also called CH4_U or METHANE-U.

Name: Clear
Description: NAC Filter #0 or #4 or WAC Filter #2, spanning portions of the Visible and Ultraviolet spectrum from 0.28 to 0.64 microns

Name: Green
Description: NAC Filter #5 or #6 or WAC Filter #5, spanning portions of the Visible spectrum from 0.53 to 0.64 microns

Name: Orange
Description: NAC Filter #3 or WAC Filter #7, spanning portions of the Visible spectrum from 0.59 to 0.64 microns

Name: Sodium
Description: WAC Filter #0, spanning portions of the Visible spectrum from 0.588 to 0.590 microns. Also called NAD or SODIUM-D.

Name: UV
Description: NAC Filter #7, spanning portions of the Ultraviolet spectrum from 0.28 to 0.37 microns

Name: Violet
Description: NAC Filter #1 or WAC Filter #3, spanning portions of the Visible and Ultraviolet spectrum from 0.35 to 0.45 microns

Name: filter_number
Description: Optical filter identification number, contains the unique number associated with the optical filter for the image. This value should correspond with that given in the definition of this label's value of filter_name. Despite the redundancy, it is retained here as it was in the source product label, for historical purposes. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword FILTER_NUMBER

Name: exposure_duration
Description: Time period during which the shutter was open Source Data Product Origin: Keyword EXPOSURE_DURATION

Name: source_product_note
Description: The observational intent of the image, as recorded in the original source product label. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword NOTE

Name: source_product_description
Description: A description of the image, as recorded in the original source product label. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword DESCRIPTION

Name: data_anomaly_type
Description: Data recording anomalies in the image. If this keyword is missing [in the source data product], no anomalies were detected. DATA_ANOMALY_TYPE = RAM_DATA_CORRUPTION indicates that spurious values exist in the image data due to corruption of the random access memory onboard the spacecraft. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword DATA_ANOMALY_TYPE

Description: Container for elements describing the process of transferring Voyager data from the spacecraft to Earth.

Description: Tape ID on which the image was originally stored Source Data Product Origin: Legacy Header

Name: edr_file_number
Description: File number within the tape where the image was originally stored Source Data Product Origin: Legacy Header

Description: Numeric ID of DSN station where the image was received Source Data Product Origin: Legacy Header

Name: Voyager_Timing
Description: Container for elements describing the time at which a data product was obtained

Name: mission_phase_name
Description: Time period within the Voyager 1 or Voyager 2 mission, as defined by the mission team. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword MISSION_PHASE_NAME

Name: Earth-Jupiter Cruise
Description: The period of cruise from Earth to Jupiter. For Voyager 1 this is 1977-09-05 to 1979-01-06. For Voyager 2 this is 1977-08-20 to 1979-04-25.

Name: Interstellar Mission
Description: The period from the final planetary encounter to the end of the mission. For Voyager 1 this is 1980-12-14 to End of Mission. For Voyager 2 this is 1989-10-02 to End of Mission.

Name: Jupiter Encounter
Description: The period surrounding the Jupiter Encounter. For Voyager 1 this is 1979-01-06 to 1979-04-13. For Voyager 2 this is 1979-04-25 to 1979-08-05.

Name: Jupiter-Saturn Cruise
Description: The period of cruise from Jupiter to Saturn. For Voyager 1 this is 1979-04-13 to 1980-08-22. For Voyager 2 this is 1979-08-05 to 1981-06-05.

Name: Launch
Description: The day of launch. For Voyager 1 this is 1977-09-05. For Voyager 2 this is 1977-08-20.

Name: Neptune Encounter
Description: The period surrounding the Neptune Encounter. This does not apply to Voyager 1. For Voyager 2 this is 1989-06-05 to 1989-10-02.

Name: Saturn Encounter
Description: The period surrounding the Saturn Encounter. For Voyager 1 this is 1980-08-22 to 1980-12-14. For Voyager 2 this is 1981-06-05 to 1981-09-25.

Name: Saturn-Uranus Cruise
Description: The period of cruise from Saturn to Uranus. This does not apply to Voyager 1. For Voyager 2 this is 1981-09-25 to 1985-11-04

Name: Uranus Encounter
Description: The period surrounding the Uranus Encounter. This does not apply to Voyager 1. For Voyager 2 this is 1985-11-04 to 1986-02-25.

Name: Uranus-Neptune Cruise
Description: The period of cruise from Uranus to Neptune. This does not apply to Voyager 1. For Voyager 2 this is 1986-02-25 to 1989-06-05.

Name: spacecraft_clock_count_partition
Description: The Voyager spacecraft clock, known as the Flight Data System (FDS), was reset to zero multiple times, dividing each mission into four

Name: spacecraft_clock_start_count
Description: The spacecraft clock value at the beginning of a time period of interest. Voyager used the term Flight Data System (FDS) for this quantity, which is equivalent to the term spacecraft clock (SCLK) more commonly used by subsequent missions. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword SPACECRAFT_CLOCK_START_COUNT

Name: spacecraft_clock_stop_count
Description: The spacecraft clock value at the end of a time period of interest. Voyager used the term Flight Data System (FDS) for this quantity, which is equivalent to the term spacecraft clock (SCLK) more commonly used by subsequent missions. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword SPACECRAFT_CLOCK_STOP_COUNT
